  <p>For all the regulatory motion in the Philippine online gaming sector over the past year &mdash; the e-wallet delinking, the GGR share-rate cut, the minimum guaranteed fee, the rebate and cashback cap, the helpline, the responsible-gaming alliance &mdash; one structural fact has remained constant: none of it rests on a comprehensive statute. The sector is governed by a stream of PAGCOR memoranda and circulars, each addressing a piece of the picture, none of them anchored in a single primary law written for online gambling as it actually exists today. That is now changing. The Senate and PAGCOR are jointly drafting a comprehensive iGaming framework intended to replace the patchwork with one unified law &mdash; and DigiPlus, the operator that controls roughly half the market, sits on the technical working group writing it.</p>

  <p>This analysis maps what a comprehensive framework would change, why the licensed industry is actively helping to build the cage it will live in, and why the drafting is happening in direct tension with the Senate camp that would prefer to ban online gambling altogether &mdash; all of it unfolding in the very weeks that the FIFA World Cup is driving Philippine betting volume to its annual peak.</p>

