  <h2>The problem the framework is meant to solve</h2>

  <p>The Philippine online gaming sector is regulated, today, by accretion. PAGCOR issues a memorandum capping rebates; another setting the minimum guaranteed fee; another adjusting the GGR share rate; another tightening KYC; another on advertising. Each is valid, each is enforceable, and together they constitute a functioning regulatory regime &mdash; but a brittle one. Memoranda can be issued, deferred, amended, or withdrawn on short notice, as the two-month deferral of the minimum guaranteed fee illustrated. They are administrative instruments, not statute, and they do not provide the kind of stable, predictable foundation that long-term capital investment prefers.</p>

  <p>For a sector that PAGCOR is simultaneously trying to formalize and consolidate, that brittleness is a problem. Operators being asked to invest in compliance infrastructure, in responsible-gaming systems, and in the scale needed to clear the new fee floor want to know the rules will not be rewritten by the next memorandum. A comprehensive law answers that want. It would gather the scattered requirements into one statutory framework, give them the durability of legislation, and provide the sector a settled basis on which to plan. The reported focus areas &mdash; payment-channel controls, marketing and advertising restrictions, and consumer protection &mdash; are exactly the domains currently governed by separate memoranda, now proposed to be unified.</p>

  <h2>The three pillars, read against what already exists</h2>

  <p>Each reported pillar of the framework is best understood as the codification and extension of a measure already in force.</p>

  <p><strong>Payment-channel controls.</strong> The 2025 BSP order that delinked e-wallets from gaming accounts was the single most consequential intervention in the sector's recent history, and it was accomplished through banking regulation rather than gaming law. Codifying payment-channel controls in a comprehensive iGaming statute would put the funding-side rules on a firmer footing and integrate them with the gaming framework rather than leaving them to the central bank. For players, this is the part of the framework that most directly governs how money moves into and out of a gaming account.</p>

  <p><strong>Marketing and advertising restrictions.</strong> The rebate and cashback cap that took effect June 1 already constrains one form of promotion. A comprehensive law would likely generalize that logic into broader advertising rules &mdash; where, how, and to whom licensed operators can market. This is also the pillar with the most obvious consumer-protection valence, given the volume of gambling advertising that the World Cup is currently pushing across Philippine feeds, and it extends the same competition dynamics analyzed in the cashback cap: rules that raise the compliance baseline tend to favor operators with the infrastructure to meet them.</p>

  <p><strong>Consumer protection.</strong> The 24-hour National Problem Gambling Helpline, the deposit-limit and self-exclusion tools, and the new PlaySafe Alliance are the current consumer-protection layer, built through a mix of regulator action and industry initiative. Codifying consumer-protection requirements in statute would make them mandatory baseline law rather than a combination of memoranda and voluntary industry standards &mdash; harder to dilute and uniform across all operators.</p>

