  <h2>Why the dominant operator is in the room</h2>

  <p>That DigiPlus sits on the technical working group is the analytically revealing detail. Industry representation in legislative drafting is common and not inherently improper, but it is never neutral. The operator helping to write the rules writes rules it can live with &mdash; and, ideally, rules it can meet more comfortably than its competitors can. This is the same pattern visible across the sector's recent regulatory development: DigiPlus supporting the rebate cap that favors scale, leading the responsible-gaming alliance that strengthens the regulate-rather-than-ban argument, and now seated at the table where the comprehensive framework is being drafted. These are three expressions of one coherent strategy &mdash; shaping the regulatory settlement the sector is moving toward, from the position of the operator most able to thrive under it.</p>

  <p>The certainty a comprehensive law offers is worth more to the incumbent than the current looseness. Statutory rules that DigiPlus can meet, codified and durable, entrench the market structure in which it already leads. A long tail of smaller operators, by contrast, faces a rising compliance baseline that scale makes easier to clear &mdash; the same consolidation pressure that the minimum fee and the rebate cap already apply, now potentially written into primary law.</p>

  <h2>The framework versus the ban</h2>

  <p>The comprehensive framework does not exist in a vacuum. It is being drafted while the Senate Committee on Games and Amusement hears a slate of bills under the Anti-Online Gambling Act umbrella, several proposing a total ban, with Senator Erwin Tulfo championing prohibition. The two efforts are opposing answers to the same question. The framework says: online gambling continues, under stronger and unified rules. The ban says: online gambling stops. Both are live in the same legislature at the same time.</p>

  <p>Understood this way, the comprehensive drafting effort is partly the licensed sector's structured alternative to prohibition &mdash; the affirmative case that the harms can be managed through a robust legal framework, offered as the reasonable middle against the ban camp's maximal position. The PlaySafe Alliance supplies the self-regulation evidence; the comprehensive framework supplies the statutory architecture; together they form the regulate-and-formalize platform that the industry is advancing against Tulfo's prohibition platform. Which prevails will define the sector for a decade.</p>

  <p>It is worth being clear-eyed about the stakes on both sides. A comprehensive framework, if it favors scale and is shaped by the dominant operator, risks codifying a concentrated market under rules written partly by its biggest beneficiary. A total ban, on the evidence of the 2024 POGO experience and the resurgent cash-and-scam underground that followed, risks pushing activity into unlicensed and offshore channels where there is no consumer protection at all. Neither outcome is costless, and the comprehensive framework's drafters are betting that a formalized legal market, whatever its concentration, is the lesser harm.</p>

  <h2>The World Cup backdrop</h2>

  <p>The timing sharpens every tension in the story. The framework is being drafted, and the ban is being debated, precisely as the FIFA World Cup &mdash; kicking off June 11 &mdash; drives Philippine betting volume to its annual peak and floods consumer feeds with gambling advertising, both licensed and offshore. The marketing-restriction pillar of the framework is being written against a live demonstration of exactly the advertising intensity it would govern. The consumer-protection pillar is being drafted while a tournament-driven surge of new and casual bettors enters the market. The ban camp, for its part, can point to the same surge as evidence of the harm it wants to prohibit. The World Cup is not just background; it is the real-time stress test that both sides of the legislative argument are watching.</p>

  <h2>The bottom line</h2>

  <p>A comprehensive iGaming law would be the most consequential single development in Philippine online gaming regulation since the sector was formalized &mdash; the moment the patchwork of memoranda becomes durable statute. It would codify payment-channel controls, marketing restrictions, and consumer protection into one framework, raise the compliance baseline in ways that favor scale, and give the licensed sector the certainty it values. It is being drafted with the dominant operator in the room and against a Senate camp that would rather ban the activity entirely.</p>

  <p>For now it is a drafting effort, not a law, and the distance between a technical working group and an enacted statute is long and politically contested. But the direction is unmistakable. The Philippines is deciding, in these months and in this legislature, whether its online gambling future is a formalized and concentrated legal market or a prohibition that pushes the activity underground. The comprehensive framework is the licensed sector's bid for the former. The World Cup is the backdrop against which the choice is being made.</p>

